Senior staff engineer:

Yes, but with one correction: the right target is not “replace the deterministic graph with an LLM graph.” The right target is “make the deterministic graph one layer inside a broader, evidence-backed context graph.”

Right now the repo is optimized for parse -> enrich -> resolve, which is good for stable linking, but narrow for reasoning. The current entity shape is centered on interfaces[], dependencies[], resolver signals, and retrieval text. That is enough to answer “what connects to what,” but not enough to reliably answer “what does this repo contribute, what feature flow does it participate in, how is data transformed, and why does this dependency exist.”

My recommendation is a conditional go:

Go for a universal knowledge graph builder.
Do not go for a freeform descriptive graph with LLM text as the source of truth.
The better architecture is:

Observation layer
Deterministic facts per repo and per commit: entrypoints, outbound calls, queues, tables, configs, schemas, docs references, ownership hints.
Semantic layer
LLM-generated but evidence-backed descriptions: purpose, capabilities, responsibilities, data consumed, data emitted, transformations, operational role, feature narratives.
Resolution layer
Canonical entities, interfaces, dependencies, placeholders for unresolved targets, and typed edges with confidence/provenance.
Retrieval layer
Context cards and embeddings for MCP/query-time reasoning.
That solves your main pain point: repos no longer need to live in one workspace. You ingest repo@commit one at a time into a persistent store, resolve it against what is already known, and keep growing the graph. Unmatched dependencies can remain as placeholder nodes until another repo is added.

I would keep interfaces and dependencies, but demote them from “the graph” to “part of the graph.” Add first-class fields or companion docs for:

purpose
capabilities
responsibilities
data_inputs
data_outputs
state_owned
transformations
feature_flows
dependency_intent
failure_impact
I’d also add a flow object type. A lot of the missing context is not an entity or interface, it is a path:

trigger
source entity/interface
target entity/interface
data moved
transformation applied
sync/async mode
business intent
evidence refs
confidence
For the MCP server, make it read-only at first and query the graph, not the repos. The useful tools are:

search_context(query)
explain_entity(id)
trace_feature(query)
trace_data_object(name)
related_repositories(query)
get_evidence(node_or_edge_id)
Bottom line: your instinct is right. The current approach is too resolver-centric to be the final product. But the fix is not to remove determinism. The fix is to introduce a layered graph where deterministic observations anchor the system and LLMs add descriptive semantics and flow reasoning on top.

If you want, I can turn this into a concrete ADR plus a revised schema for kg_observations, kg_entities, kg_flows, and the MCP API surface.

