Senior staff engineer:

Using agentic-ai-system-design here because this is a workflow architecture decision, not just a schema tweak.

Not fully hand-in-hand in the sense of “LLM and parser co-own extraction.” That would make the system weaker.

The problem with a fully merged pipeline is:

determinism gets diluted
replay becomes harder
caching by repo@commit gets worse
testing becomes harder because parser facts are no longer stable
cost/latency rises because the LLM gets dragged into basic extraction work
you lose a clean source of truth when the model hallucinates or over-interprets
The better update is a hybrid pipeline:

Baseline parse
Deterministically extract cheap, broad observations across the repo.
Agent-guided exploration
The enricher reads the baseline and asks for targeted deeper parses only where needed.
Structured semantic synthesis
The agent produces descriptions, flow summaries, capability narratives, and candidate links using the deterministic evidence.
Resolution/persistence
Store observations, semantic summaries, unresolved placeholders, and resolved edges separately.
So yes, parse and enrich should work more closely together, but not as one fused step. The parser should remain the fact engine, and the agent should drive iterative deepening.

A better mental model is:

not parse -> enrich
not parse + enrich collapsed
but parse -> enrich asks for more parse -> enrich -> resolve
Concretely, I’d change the system toward:

repo scanner
observation extractor
targeted extraction tools for routes, schemas, message flows, configs, docs
semantic enricher
resolver
MCP query server
This gives you the benefit you want:

richer descriptions
better reasoning
better feature-flow understanding
no need to load all repos into one workspace
If you want, I can draft the revised pipeline as a concrete V2 design with stages, tool contracts, and schema changes.

