Senior staff engineer:

Yes. What you’re describing is a real production issue, not an edge case.

For API-to-API calls, code often does not contain the final target URL at all. It usually contains:

a client name
a config key
a service alias
a route template
a gateway path
an SDK wrapper
The actual destination is then decided by environment config, service discovery, API gateway rules, Helm values, secrets, or deployment metadata. So if the current graph expects exact provider resolution from repo code alone, it will always be incomplete.  it is still too thin for this reality.

The same is true for MFE systems. A repo may only show:

shell-to-remote registration
route mounting
Module Federation remotes
manifest lookup
feature flags
nested composition
At runtime, the actual UI tree can be much more dynamic than repo structure suggests.

So the correct answer is:

Yes, reasoning can help derive these relations.
No, reasoning alone should not be treated as final truth.
The graph should support three different kinds of relation:

Observed
Direct evidence from code, config, manifest, docs, or runtime telemetry.
Inferred
High-confidence semantic guess from the LLM based on evidence.
Resolved
Confirmed canonical link after enough evidence exists.
For example, instead of forcing:

“UI A calls Service B”
store:

“UI A appears to depend on pricing capability”
evidence: client registration, route /pricing, config key pricingApiBaseUrl
inferred candidates: pricing-api, pricing-gateway
confidence: 0.63
missing evidence: runtime binding / deployment config
That is the right way to handle dynamic repos.

What this means for the product design:

code graph alone is not enough
semantic graph alone is not enough
you need a context graph made of code observations, config/deployment observations, runtime observations, and LLM inferences
For your API and MFE cases, I would explicitly add new node/edge types:

config_binding
runtime_endpoint
gateway_route
ui_shell
mfe_remote
mounts
hosts
composes
loads_dynamically
depends_on_capability
So yes, your broader direction is correct. The graph becomes useful when it can represent uncertainty, indirection, and runtime composition, instead of pretending every dependency is a clean static code link.

If you want, I can draft the V2 schema additions specifically for:

dynamic API resolution
MFE composition and nested UI graphs
inferred vs observed edge confidence model

