Senior staff engineer:

Using agentic-ai-system-design here because this is still an architecture choice.

I agree with your pushback on over-modeling. If you turn every concept into a rigid node type up front, you will recreate a brittle enterprise schema and the system will stop matching real repos.

But description-only is too far in the other direction.

What works better is:

keep the graph very thin and generic
store rich descriptive evidence alongside it
let the LLM infer meaning at query time
So instead of designing many deterministic node types like mfe_remote, gateway_route, config_binding, I would keep only a minimal substrate such as:

artifact or entity
observation
relation
evidence
Then put the real value in text:

what this repo appears to do
how it communicates
what other systems it likely depends on
what runtime indirections exist
what is explicit vs inferred
what evidence supports that reading
Why you still need that thin structure:

the agent needs anchors to retrieve the right context
you need provenance for trust and debugging
you need incremental updates as repos are added
you need to avoid one giant blob of text per repo
you need to connect descriptions across repos somehow
So I would phrase it like this:

Not a deterministic legacy schema.
Not a pure freeform narrative store.
A lightly structured evidence graph with description-first semantics.

That gives you the flexibility you want while still making the system operable.

The practical rule should be:

schema for storage, retrieval, provenance, and linking
descriptions for meaning, behavior, intent, and dynamic runtime interpretation
If you remove almost all structure and rely only on LLM inference, the first demo may look good, but cross-repo consistency, update handling, and conflict resolution will get weak very quickly.

So yes, reduce schema pressure aggressively. But do not remove the minimal anchors the agent needs to reason over the corpus.


