Senior staff engineer:

To make it broadly usable across real repos, I would optimize for these properties:

Evidence-first, not schema-first
Every important claim should carry evidence pointers. The graph can be descriptive, but it cannot become pure narrative. If the agent says “this service likely powers pricing,” it should also say why.

Support uncertainty as a first-class concept
Real repos are incomplete, dynamic, and environment-dependent. So the graph must allow:

known
inferred
ambiguous
conflicting
unresolved
If you force early certainty, the graph becomes wrong quickly.

Ingest incrementally by repo + commit, not by giant workspace
A universal system should work one repo at a time and gradually improve as more repos are added. It should never depend on “clone everything into one folder first.”

Treat code as only one source of context
A robust graph should accept:

code
configs
manifests
CI/CD files
API specs
docs
runtime logs or traces later
deployment metadata later
If you only rely on source code, dynamic systems will always look incomplete.

Keep the hard schema minimal and durable
Only make stable fields rigid:
identity
source/provenance
evidence
object type at a broad level
contracts/data exchange anchors
timestamps/versioning
Everything else should be flexible descriptive payload.

Add rich natural-language descriptions at every level
Not just repo/entity level. Also:
interface: what it does, when it is used, what it accepts/returns, what side effects it has
dependency: why it exists, what capability it relies on, what data it sends or expects back
relation: what this connection means in business terms
flow: what happens end to end
Separate observations from interpretations
This is important. Store:
raw or normalized observations
semantic descriptions generated from them
That way better models can reinterpret old evidence later without re-parsing the whole world.

Make the graph temporal
Repos change. Interfaces move. MFEs remount. APIs split. The graph should understand “true at this commit / time window,” not pretend everything is permanent.

Design for partial graphs
The system should still be useful when only 10% of the ecosystem is ingested. That means placeholder targets, open questions, and inferred links must be allowed.

Query-time reasoning should be more important than ingest-time overfitting
Do not try to encode every possible concept during graph creation. Store enough good context so the LLM can assemble the right answer later.

Add evaluation early
A universal graph is only useful if you can test:

does it identify the right repo for a feature?
does it trace likely upstream/downstream systems?
does it explain data flow correctly?
does it surface uncertainty instead of making things up?
Prefer “capability understanding” over “technology classification”
Universal systems fail when they overfocus on framework-specific parsing. The graph should answer:

what does this thing contribute?
what does it expose?
what does it depend on?
what data does it handle?
what feature flow does it belong to?
That is much more reusable than framework-heavy modeling.

If I compress all of this into one rule:

Build a graph that is evidence-backed, uncertainty-aware, incrementally ingestible, and description-rich at every level, while keeping only the minimum schema needed for retrieval, provenance, and linking.

The biggest mistakes to avoid are:

too much rigid schema
too little provenance
forcing certainty too early
assuming code alone tells the truth
trying to fully resolve everything at ingest time
If you want, I can next turn this into a short set of design principles for the project, like 8-10 rules you can keep as the foundation for the V2 rewrite.


